const moduleData = [
  {
    moduleNumber: 1,
    title: "Site Preparation & Permitting",
    description: "Learn the fundamentals of site preparation including surveying, clearing, grubbing, erosion control, and the permitting process.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Understand property line identification and building setbacks</li>
      <li>Master site preparation techniques including clearing and grading</li>
      <li>Navigate the permitting and inspection process</li>
      <li>Implement proper erosion control measures</li>
      <li>Coordinate trade partners and site logistics</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This foundational stage is one of the most critical, as it sets the stage for the entire project. Errors or oversights here can cause significant delays and budget overruns. It involves transforming a raw piece of land into a build-ready site while navigating the necessary legal and administrative hurdles.</p>

    <h3>Surveyor Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Property Line and Setback Identification</h4>
    <p>The surveyor researches the legal plat of the property to identify the exact boundaries. They physically locate and mark the property corners with stakes and flagging. They also mark the building setbacks, which are the minimum distances the structure must be from the property lines, as dictated by local zoning ordinances.</p>

    <h4>House Staking</h4>
    <p>Using the approved architectural plans, the surveyor stakes out the precise footprint of the house on the lot. This includes marking the corners of the foundation and any other critical points that the excavation and foundation contractors will use as a guide. The stakes must be accurate to within a fraction of an inch to ensure the house is built in the correct location and orientation.</p>

    <h3>Site Prep Contractor Activities</h3>
    <h4>Clearing and Grubbing</h4>
    <p>All trees, brush, and vegetation within the construction zone are removed. Trees designated to be saved are clearly marked and protected. The root systems of removed trees are grubbed out to prevent future settling and decay.</p>

    <h4>Erosion Control</h4>
    <p>Silt fences or other erosion control measures are installed around the perimeter of the disturbed area to prevent soil from washing off-site during rain, a common requirement before any major grading can begin.</p>

    <h4>Rough Grading</h4>
    <p>Using heavy equipment like bulldozers and graders, the contractor reshapes the lot to create the basic contours for proper drainage, as shown on the site plan. This involves cutting high spots and filling low spots to create a level building pad and to ensure water will flow away from the future foundation.</p>

    <h4>Access Road and Staging Area</h4>
    <p>A temporary construction driveway is created using gravel or crushed rock to provide a stable surface for heavy vehicles and to minimize mud being tracked onto public roads. A staging area is designated for material deliveries and parking.</p>

    <h4>Temporary Utilities</h4>
    <p>A temporary electrical pole and panel are installed by a licensed electrician and inspected by the utility company. A temporary water meter or connection to a well is established for construction use.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Role</h3>
    <h4>Permit Review and Approval</h4>
    <p>The inspector or plans examiner meticulously reviews the submitted building plans and engineering documents for compliance with all local building codes, zoning laws, and ordinances. This includes structural, electrical, plumbing, mechanical, and energy codes. Once approved, the building permit is issued, which must be prominently displayed on the job site.</p>

    <h4>Initial Site/Erosion Control Inspection</h4>
    <p>Before major earthmoving, an inspector may visit the site to verify that the required erosion control measures are correctly installed. They will check that the silt fence is properly trenched and staked to effectively contain sediment.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Oversight</h3>
    <h4>Coordination and Scheduling</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the surveyor and site prep contractor in the correct sequence. They ensure that the surveyor has the final approved plans to work from.</p>

    <h4>Permitting and Documentation</h4>
    <p>The CM is responsible for compiling and submitting the complete permit application package to the city, which may include multiple sets of plans, engineering calculations, soil reports, and other documents. They track the permit through the review process and respond to any questions or requests for additional information from the city.</p>

    <h4>Pre-Construction Verification</h4>
    <p>The CM verifies that all conditions from the land department or developer have been met before work begins (e.g., architectural review committee approval, tree preservation plans).</p>

    <h4>Site Logistics and Safety</h4>
    <p>The CM establishes the site layout, including the location of the temporary utilities, construction entrance, material storage, and waste dumpster. A comprehensive site safety plan is developed and communicated to all trade partners, including requirements for personal protective equipment (PPE) and emergency procedures.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 1
  },
  {
    moduleNumber: 2,
    title: "Foundation",
    description: "Master foundation construction from excavation to waterproofing, including footings, foundation walls, and under-slab plumbing.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Understand excavation and hole preparation techniques</li>
      <li>Master footing and foundation wall construction</li>
      <li>Learn proper waterproofing and drainage installation</li>
      <li>Coordinate under-slab plumbing installation</li>
      <li>Navigate foundation inspection requirements</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This stage is where the house gets its structural base. The foundation must be strong, square, and level to support the weight of the entire house and resist the forces of the surrounding soil. Precision is paramount in this stage.</p>

    <h3>Excavator Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Hole Excavation</h4>
    <p>Following the surveyor's stakes, the excavator digs the hole for the foundation to the depth specified in the plans. The soil is stockpiled on-site in a designated location, to be used for backfilling later. The bottom of the excavation must be level and undisturbed soil.</p>

    <h4>Utility Trenching</h4>
    <p>The excavator also digs trenches for the underground utilities (water, sewer, gas, electrical conduit) from the street to the house.</p>

    <h3>Concrete Contractor Work</h3>
    <h4>Footing Construction</h4>
    <p>Forms (temporary molds) are set up in the bottom of the excavation to create the shape of the footings. Steel reinforcing bars (rebar) are placed inside the forms to add strength to the concrete. The concrete is poured into the forms and allowed to cure.</p>

    <h4>Foundation Wall Construction</h4>
    <p>Forms are set up on top of the footings for the foundation walls. Rebar is placed within the forms, and anchor bolts are set into the top of the wall to later secure the wood framing. The concrete is poured into the forms and vibrated to remove air pockets.</p>

    <h4>Waterproofing and Drainage</h4>
    <p>After the forms are removed, a waterproofing membrane or coating is applied to the exterior of the foundation walls. A perforated drain pipe (foundation drain or footing drain) is installed around the base of the foundation and covered with gravel to collect and carry away groundwater.</p>

    <h4>Slab Pouring</h4>
    <p>A layer of gravel and a vapor barrier are placed on the ground inside the foundation. The concrete for the basement floor or slab-on-grade is poured and finished to a smooth, level surface.</p>

    <h3>Plumber Tasks</h3>
    <h4>Under-Slab Rough-In</h4>
    <p>Before the slab is poured, the plumber installs all the plumbing pipes that will be located underneath the concrete floor. This includes drains for sinks, showers, and toilets, as well as any water supply lines that need to be run under the slab.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Requirements</h3>
    <h4>Footing Inspection</h4>
    <p>The inspector verifies that the footing trenches are dug to the correct depth and width. They check the placement and size of the rebar to ensure it meets the structural plans. The ground must be free of loose soil and debris. This inspection must pass before any concrete is poured.</p>

    <h4>Foundation/Under-Slab Inspection</h4>
    <p>The inspector checks the foundation walls for proper height, thickness, and rebar placement. They inspect the waterproofing and drainage system to ensure it is installed correctly. They also inspect the under-slab plumbing to make sure it is properly sloped and connected. This inspection must pass before backfilling.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Role</h3>
    <h4>Scheduling and Coordination</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the excavator, concrete contractor, and plumber in the correct sequence, ensuring no delays between trades. They coordinate the delivery of concrete and other materials.</p>

    <h4>Quality Control</h4>
    <p>The CM verifies the foundation layout and dimensions against the plans. They inspect the work of each trade to ensure it meets quality standards. They ensure the foundation is square and level.</p>

    <h4>Inspection Management</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules all required city inspections and is present on-site to meet with the inspector. If an inspection fails, the CM is responsible for ensuring the corrections are made and the re-inspection is scheduled and passed.</p>

    <h4>Backfilling Authorization</h4>
    <p>The CM authorizes the excavator to backfill around the foundation only after the foundation inspection has been approved.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 2
  },
  {
    moduleNumber: 3,
    title: "Framing",
    description: "Build the structural skeleton of the house including floor systems, walls, roof structure, windows, and doors.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Master floor system construction techniques</li>
      <li>Understand wall assembly and installation</li>
      <li>Learn roof and ceiling construction methods</li>
      <li>Navigate window and door installation</li>
      <li>Pass comprehensive framing inspections</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>During the framing stage, the house transforms from a concrete slab into a recognizable structure. This is often considered one of the most exciting phases for a homeowner to watch. The framing creates the "skeleton" of the house, defining all the rooms, walls, and rooflines. Accuracy is critical, as all subsequent trades will rely on the framing being plumb, level, and square.</p>

    <h3>Framing Contractor Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Floor System Construction</h4>
    <p>The contractor lays down a sill plate, which is pressure-treated lumber bolted directly to the foundation wall. Floor joists (or pre-engineered floor trusses) are set on top of the sill plate, spaced according to the plans (typically 16 or 24 inches on center). Rim joists are installed around the perimeter. The subfloor, typically 3/4-inch plywood or OSB (Oriented Strand Board), is glued and nailed to the joists, creating the walking surface for the first floor.</p>

    <h4>Wall Assembly</h4>
    <p>Walls are typically assembled on the subfloor and then lifted into place. Each wall section consists of top and bottom plates, vertical studs, and headers over window and door openings. Exterior walls are sheathed with plywood or OSB, which adds significant structural strength and a nailing surface for siding.</p>

    <h4>Roof and Ceiling Assembly</h4>
    <p>Ceiling joists are installed to form the structure of the ceiling. The roof is constructed using either pre-fabricated trusses delivered to the site or by stick-building with individual rafters. The trusses or rafters are lifted into place (often with a crane) and secured, creating the pitch and shape of the roof. The roof is then sheathed with OSB or plywood, creating the roof deck.</p>

    <h4>Window and Door Installation</h4>
    <p>Windows and exterior doors are installed into the prepared openings. Proper flashing and sealing around these units are critical to prevent water intrusion.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Requirements</h3>
    <h4>Framing Inspection (Shear/Structural Inspection)</h4>
    <p>This is one of the most comprehensive and critical inspections. The inspector will walk the entire structure, often with the plans in hand.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Structural Integrity:</strong> They verify that all lumber and beams are the correct size and grade, that joist and rafter spans are not exceeded, and that all structural connections (e.g., hurricane ties, anchor bolts) are correctly installed.</li>
      <li><strong>Load Path:</strong> The inspector checks to ensure there is a continuous load path, meaning the weight from the roof is properly transferred all the way down to the foundation.</li>
      <li><strong>Nailing and Fastening:</strong> They will check the nailing patterns on the sheathing and other structural components to ensure they meet the required shear strength.</li>
      <li><strong>Openings:</strong> Headers over windows and doors are checked to ensure they are sized correctly for the load they are carrying.</li>
      <li><strong>Code Compliance:</strong> The inspector checks for compliance with numerous other code requirements, such as fire blocking between floors and in specific wall cavities.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This inspection must pass before any plumbing, electrical, or mechanical work can be covered up.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Role</h3>
    <h4>Material Management</h4>
    <p>The CM is responsible for doing a "take-off" (calculating the amount of lumber needed) from the plans and ordering the lumber package. They coordinate the delivery of materials to the site, ensuring they are stored properly and protected from the weather.</p>

    <h4>Quality Control and Oversight</h4>
    <p>The CM is on-site daily during framing to oversee the contractor. They check that walls are being built square and plumb, that dimensions are correct, and that the framing matches the architectural plans exactly. They ensure the framers are following all safety protocols.</p>

    <h4>Scheduling and Coordination</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the framing inspection with the city once the work is complete. They coordinate with the plumber and electrician, who may need to drill holes through the framing for their pipes and wires before the inspection.</p>

    <h4>Pre-Inspection Walkthrough</h4>
    <p>Before the official inspector arrives, the CM conducts a thorough walkthrough with the framing contractor's foreman. They use a checklist to look for common failure points and ensure everything is ready for the inspector. This proactive step is crucial for avoiding costly delays from a failed inspection.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 3
  },
  {
    moduleNumber: 4,
    title: "Exterior Finishes",
    description: "Learn how to weatherproof the house with roofing, siding, and exterior trim installation to protect the investment.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Master roofing installation and waterproofing techniques</li>
      <li>Understand siding and exterior cladding systems</li>
      <li>Learn proper flashing and weather barrier installation</li>
      <li>Coordinate exterior finish scheduling</li>
      <li>Implement weather protection strategies</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This stage is often referred to as "drying-in" the house. The goal is to make the structure weatherproof so that interior work can proceed without risk of water damage. This stage protects the investment made in the framing and prepares the house for the mechanical rough-in.</p>

    <h3>Roofing Contractor Work</h3>
    <h4>Underlayment Installation</h4>
    <p>A water-resistant underlayment (felt paper or synthetic membrane) is installed over the roof deck to provide a secondary layer of protection. In areas prone to ice dams, an ice and water shield is installed along the eaves and valleys.</p>

    <h4>Roofing Material Installation</h4>
    <p>Asphalt shingles are the most common residential roofing material. They are installed starting from the bottom edge of the roof and working upward, with each row overlapping the one below. Metal roofing, tile, or other materials follow their specific installation procedures. Proper nailing patterns and exposure are critical for wind resistance and longevity.</p>

    <h4>Flashing Installation</h4>
    <p>Metal flashing is installed around all roof penetrations (chimneys, plumbing vents, skylights) and in valleys to direct water away and prevent leaks. Step flashing is installed where the roof meets a vertical wall.</p>

    <h3>Siding/Masonry Contractor Tasks</h3>
    <h4>Weather-Resistant Barrier</h4>
    <p>A house wrap or building paper is installed over the exterior sheathing to provide a weather-resistant barrier while still allowing moisture vapor to escape from inside the wall.</p>

    <h4>Siding Installation</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Vinyl Siding:</strong> Installed with starter strips at the bottom and then overlapping courses working upward.</li>
      <li><strong>Fiber Cement Siding:</strong> Nailed or screwed to the wall, with proper spacing for expansion and contraction.</li>
      <li><strong>Wood Siding:</strong> Requires careful attention to painting or staining for protection.</li>
      <li><strong>Brick or Stone Veneer:</strong> Laid up against the exterior wall, with metal ties connecting it to the structure and weep holes at the bottom to allow moisture to escape.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Exterior Trim</h4>
    <p>Trim boards are installed around windows, doors, corners, and along the roofline to provide a finished appearance and additional weather protection.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Requirements</h3>
    <h4>Sheathing Inspection</h4>
    <p>This may be part of the framing inspection. The inspector checks that the sheathing is properly attached to resist wind uplift and racking.</p>

    <h4>Roofing Inspection</h4>
    <p>The inspector verifies that the underlayment is installed correctly and that the roofing material is installed according to manufacturer specifications and code requirements. They check flashing details to ensure they will effectively shed water.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Scheduling and Coordination</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the roofing contractor immediately after the framing inspection passes to get the house dried-in as quickly as possible. They coordinate the siding contractor to begin work as soon as the roofing is complete.</p>

    <h4>Quality Control</h4>
    <p>The CM inspects the roof for proper installation, looking for any exposed nails, improperly aligned shingles, or inadequate flashing. They check the siding for straightness, proper overlap, and secure attachment.</p>

    <h4>Weather Protection</h4>
    <p>The CM ensures that any openings (windows, doors) are properly sealed and that the house is secure from the elements before the end of each workday.</p>

    <h4>Scaffolding and Safety</h4>
    <p>The CM coordinates the rental and setup of scaffolding or lifts as needed for safe access to the exterior walls and roof.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 4
  },
  {
    moduleNumber: 5,
    title: "Rough-In Mechanicals",
    description: "Install the essential systems including HVAC, plumbing, and electrical rough-in work that will be hidden behind walls.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Understand HVAC equipment and ductwork installation</li>
      <li>Master plumbing rough-in techniques and requirements</li>
      <li>Learn electrical wiring and panel installation</li>
      <li>Coordinate multiple trade partners effectively</li>
      <li>Navigate comprehensive rough-in inspections</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This is the stage where the "guts" of the house are installed—all the systems that will be hidden behind the walls. Coordination between the three major trades (HVAC, plumbing, electrical) is essential, as their work often intersects and must be carefully planned to avoid conflicts.</p>

    <h3>HVAC Contractor Work</h3>
    <h4>Equipment Installation</h4>
    <p>The furnace and/or air handler is set in place, typically in a mechanical room, basement, or attic. The outdoor condenser unit for the air conditioning system is set on a pad outside the house.</p>

    <h4>Ductwork Installation</h4>
    <p>Supply ducts are run from the furnace/air handler to each room, terminating in locations where registers will be installed. Return air ducts are installed to bring air back to the furnace/air handler. Ducts are typically made of sheet metal or flexible insulated ducting. All duct joints are sealed with mastic or metal tape (not cloth duct tape) to prevent air leakage.</p>

    <h4>Venting</h4>
    <p>Exhaust vents for bathrooms and the kitchen range hood are installed, venting to the outside. The furnace combustion vent is installed according to code.</p>

    <h3>Plumber Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Water Supply Lines</h4>
    <p>Hot and cold water lines (typically PEX, copper, or CPVC) are run from the main water line to each fixture location (sinks, toilets, showers, washing machine, etc.). Lines are secured to the framing and protected from potential damage.</p>

    <h4>Drain, Waste, and Vent (DWV) System</h4>
    <p>Drain pipes (typically PVC or ABS) are installed from each fixture, sloping downward to carry waste to the main sewer line or septic system. Vent pipes are run upward through the roof to allow sewer gases to escape and to equalize pressure in the drain system. The plumber must ensure proper slope and venting for all drains.</p>

    <h4>Fixture Rough-In</h4>
    <p>Shower and tub units are set in place (the actual faucets and trim are installed later). Stub-outs (short pipe extensions) are installed at the correct height and location for sinks, toilets, and other fixtures.</p>

    <h3>Electrician Tasks</h3>
    <h4>Service Panel Installation</h4>
    <p>The main electrical panel (breaker box) is installed, typically in the garage, basement, or utility room. The meter base is installed on the exterior of the house.</p>

    <h4>Wiring Installation</h4>
    <p>Electrical wire (typically Romex cable) is run from the panel to every outlet, switch, and light fixture location. Wires are pulled through holes drilled in the framing and secured with staples. Separate circuits are run for high-draw appliances (oven, dryer, water heater, HVAC).</p>

    <h4>Boxes and Devices</h4>
    <p>Electrical boxes are installed at every outlet, switch, and fixture location. Wires are brought into the boxes and left with enough slack for later connection to devices.</p>

    <h4>Special Systems</h4>
    <p>Wiring for phone, data (ethernet), cable TV, doorbell, and security systems is installed.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Requirements</h3>
    <h4>Rough-In Inspection (Mechanical, Plumbing, Electrical)</h4>
    <p>This is a comprehensive inspection that may be done as a single visit or as separate inspections for each trade.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>HVAC:</strong> The inspector checks duct sizing, proper support and sealing, clearances around equipment, and proper venting of combustion appliances.</li>
      <li><strong>Plumbing:</strong> The inspector verifies proper pipe sizing, slope of drains, proper venting, secure attachment, and may require a pressure test of the water lines and a drain test.</li>
      <li><strong>Electrical:</strong> The inspector checks wire sizing for the amperage, proper grounding and bonding, correct box fill, proper support of cables, and that all connections are made in accessible boxes.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This inspection must pass before insulation and drywall can be installed.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Role</h3>
    <h4>Trade Coordination</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the HVAC, plumbing, and electrical contractors in a coordinated sequence, often with some overlap. They hold coordination meetings to resolve conflicts where ductwork, pipes, and wires intersect.</p>

    <h4>Quality Control</h4>
    <p>The CM walks the job site regularly during rough-in to ensure work is progressing correctly. They check that all systems are being installed according to the plans and that the work is neat and professional.</p>

    <h4>Pre-Inspection Walkthrough</h4>
    <p>Before calling for the rough-in inspection, the CM does a detailed walkthrough with each trade contractor. They use a checklist to verify that all work is complete and ready for inspection.</p>

    <h4>Inspection Management</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the rough-in inspection(s) and is present to meet with the inspector and answer any questions. If any issues are identified, the CM ensures they are corrected promptly and schedules the re-inspection.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 5
