    moduleNumber: 7,
    title: "Interior Finishes",
    description: "Bring the house to life with painting, trim, cabinets, flooring, and countertops that define the home's character.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Master interior painting and surface preparation</li>
      <li>Understand trim and carpentry installation</li>
      <li>Learn flooring installation techniques</li>
      <li>Coordinate cabinet and countertop installation</li>
      <li>Manage trade sequencing to protect finished surfaces</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This is where the house truly comes to life. The interior finishes give the house its character and style. This stage requires careful sequencing to protect finished surfaces from damage by subsequent trades.</p>

    <h3>Painting Contractor Work</h3>
    <h4>Surface Preparation</h4>
    <p>All drywall surfaces are primed with a drywall primer/sealer. Any remaining imperfections are filled and sanded.</p>

    <h4>Caulking</h4>
    <p>Caulk is applied to all joints where trim will meet the walls and ceilings to create a seamless appearance.</p>

    <h4>Painting</h4>
    <p>Two coats of paint are typically applied to walls and ceilings. Trim is primed and painted (often before installation, or after).</p>

    <h3>Carpentry Contractor Tasks</h3>
    <h4>Interior Door Installation</h4>
    <p>Pre-hung interior doors are set into the rough openings and shimmed to be level and plumb. Door casings (trim around the door) are installed.</p>

    <h4>Baseboard and Trim Installation</h4>
    <p>Baseboards are installed along the bottom of all walls. Crown molding (if specified) is installed where the walls meet the ceiling. Window sills and casings are installed.</p>

    <h4>Cabinet Installation</h4>
    <p>Kitchen cabinets are set in place, leveled, and secured to the walls. Bathroom vanities are installed.</p>

    <h4>Shelving and Closet Systems</h4>
    <p>Closet rods and shelving are installed.</p>

    <h3>Flooring Contractor Work</h3>
    <h4>Hardwood Flooring</h4>
    <p>Hardwood planks are nailed or glued to the subfloor. The floor is sanded smooth and finished with stain and polyurethane.</p>

    <h4>Tile Flooring</h4>
    <p>Tile is set in thin-set mortar on the subfloor or a cement backer board. Grout is applied between the tiles and sealed.</p>

    <h4>Vinyl or Laminate Flooring</h4>
    <p>Vinyl planks or laminate flooring is installed as a floating floor over an underlayment.</p>

    <h4>Carpet</h4>
    <p>Carpet padding is laid down, and carpet is stretched and tacked into place.</p>

    <h3>Countertop Fabricator Process</h3>
    <h4>Templating</h4>
    <p>After cabinets are installed, the fabricator creates a precise template of the countertop area.</p>

    <h4>Fabrication</h4>
    <p>The countertop (granite, quartz, laminate, etc.) is cut to size and edges are finished. Holes are cut for sinks and faucets.</p>

    <h4>Installation</h4>
    <p>The countertop is set on top of the cabinets and secured. Seams are joined and sealed.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Role</h3>
    <h4>Sequencing</h4>
    <p>The CM carefully sequences the interior finish trades to minimize damage. Typically: paint first, then trim and cabinets, then flooring, then final paint touch-up.</p>

    <h4>Protection</h4>
    <p>The CM ensures that finished surfaces are protected. For example, hardwood floors are covered with cardboard or protective paper after installation.</p>

    <h4>Quality Control</h4>
    <p>The CM inspects all finish work for quality, ensuring paint is smooth, trim joints are tight, cabinets are level, and flooring is installed correctly.</p>

    <h4>Material Coordination</h4>
    <p>The CM ensures that all finish materials (paint colors, flooring, cabinets, countertops) are selected, ordered, and delivered on time.</p>
  </section>
</div>
