  {
    moduleNumber: 9,
    title: "Final Finishes & Cleaning",
    description: "Complete all final details including appliance installation, hardware, touch-up painting, and thorough cleaning.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Understand appliance installation and testing procedures</li>
      <li>Master hardware installation techniques</li>
      <li>Learn final paint touch-up and quality control</li>
      <li>Implement comprehensive cleaning protocols</li>
      <li>Manage punch list creation and completion</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This stage involves the final details that make the house move-in ready. Every last item is installed, every surface is cleaned, and the house is prepared for the homeowner.</p>

    <h3>Appliance Installer Work</h3>
    <h4>Appliance Delivery and Installation</h4>
    <p>Major appliances (refrigerator, stove, dishwasher, microwave, washer, dryer) are delivered and installed. All appliances are tested for proper operation.</p>

    <h3>Hardware Installer Tasks</h3>
    <h4>Door Hardware</h4>
    <p>Door handles, knobs, and locks are installed on all interior and exterior doors.</p>

    <h4>Cabinet Hardware</h4>
    <p>Knobs and pulls are installed on all cabinet doors and drawers.</p>

    <h4>Bathroom Accessories</h4>
    <p>Towel bars, toilet paper holders, and other bathroom accessories are installed.</p>

    <h3>Painting Contractor Final Work</h3>
    <h4>Final Touch-Up</h4>
    <p>The painter returns to touch up any areas that were damaged or marked during the installation of trim, cabinets, or flooring. All walls, ceilings, and trim are inspected and any imperfections are corrected.</p>

    <h3>Cleaning Crew Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Construction Cleaning</h4>
    <p>All construction dust and debris are removed from the entire house. All surfaces (countertops, cabinets, fixtures) are wiped down. Floors are thoroughly cleaned (swept, mopped, or vacuumed). Windows are cleaned inside and out. All stickers and protective coverings are removed from appliances and fixtures.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Role</h3>
    <h4>Punch List Creation</h4>
    <p>The CM walks the entire house with a detailed checklist, identifying any items that need correction or completion. This "punch list" is given to the appropriate contractors.</p>

    <h4>Punch List Management</h4>
    <p>The CM ensures that all punch list items are completed.</p>

    <h4>Final Preparations</h4>
    <p>The CM ensures the house is spotless and ready for the final walkthrough with the homeowner.</p>

    <h4>Documentation</h4>
    <p>The CM compiles all warranties, manuals, and maintenance information for the homeowner.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 9
  },
  {
    moduleNumber: 10,
    title: "Final Walkthrough & Handover",
    description: "Complete the final inspection, obtain certificate of occupancy, and conduct homeowner orientation and handover.",
    content: `
<div class="module-content">
  <section class="learning-objectives">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Navigate the final building inspection process</li>
      <li>Understand certificate of occupancy requirements</li>
      <li>Master homeowner orientation and walkthrough procedures</li>
      <li>Learn project closeout and documentation</li>
      <li>Complete successful project handover</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This is the culmination of the entire construction process. The house is inspected one last time by the city, and then the keys are handed over to the homeowner.</p>

    <h3>Homeowner Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Final Walkthrough</h4>
    <p>The homeowner walks through the entire house with the Construction Manager. They inspect all rooms, systems, and finishes. They test all appliances, fixtures, lights, and systems. They identify any items that need correction and add them to the punch list.</p>

    <h4>Homeowner Orientation</h4>
    <p>The CM provides an orientation, explaining how to operate all systems and appliances. The homeowner receives all keys, garage door openers, and alarm codes.</p>

    <h4>Documentation Receipt</h4>
    <p>The homeowner receives all warranties, manuals, and maintenance schedules. They receive a copy of the final approved plans and the Certificate of Occupancy.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Final Work</h3>
    <h4>Final Building Inspection</h4>
    <p>This is the last and most comprehensive inspection. The inspector walks through the entire house, checking that all work is complete and meets code. They verify that all previous inspections have been passed. They check for proper egress (emergency exits) from bedrooms. They verify that smoke and carbon monoxide detectors are installed and functional. They check handrails, guardrails, and other safety features.</p>

    <h4>Certificate of Occupancy (CO)</h4>
    <p>If the final inspection passes, the inspector issues a Certificate of Occupancy, which legally allows the homeowner to move in and occupy the house.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Final Role</h3>
    <h4>Pre-Final Inspection</h4>
    <p>The CM conducts a thorough inspection of the house before calling for the final city inspection to ensure everything is ready.</p>

    <h4>Final Inspection Scheduling</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the final building inspection with the city. They are present during the inspection to answer questions and address any issues.</p>

    <h4>Final Walkthrough Coordination</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules and conducts the final walkthrough with the homeowner. They explain all systems and answer all questions.</p>

    <h4>Punch List Completion</h4>
    <p>Any items identified during the final walkthrough or final inspection are added to the punch list and completed promptly.</p>

    <h4>Certificate of Occupancy</h4>
    <p>The CM obtains the Certificate of Occupancy from the city and provides a copy to the homeowner.</p>

    <h4>Project Closeout</h4>
    <p>The CM completes all final paperwork, including lien releases from all contractors and suppliers. They ensure all warranties are transferred to the homeowner. They provide the homeowner with a complete set of as-built plans (if any changes were made during construction).</p>

    <h4>Handover</h4>
    <p>The CM officially hands over the completed house to the homeowner, marking the successful completion of the project.</p>
  </section>
</div>
    `,
    order: 10
  }
];

